INSERT INTO `ttc_posts` VALUES (8,'A Quick Summary of Current Fair Trade Pricing','a-quick-summary-of-current-fair-trade-pricing','	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"left\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font style=\"font-size: 10pt\"><font face=\"helvetica\" color=\"#443f3f\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt;\"><font>The\r\nbasic aim of the&nbsp;</font></font><font color=\"#443f3f\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i>Transparent\r\nTrade Coffee</i></font></font><font color=\"#443f3f\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt;\">&nbsp;program\r\nis to address the issue of appropriate compensation for farmers who\r\ngrow beans for roasters selling into the specialty coffee segment. But does it offer appropriate support for farmers who participate in specialty markets? The TT Coffee team explores.</font></font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><br></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <img src=\"http://transparenttradecoffee.com/app/uploads/blog/1650842832T8xltSI.png\" height=\"286\" width=\"507\"><br></p>','	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font><font face=\"helvetica\" color=\"#443f3f\" size=\"4\"><font><font>The\r\nbasic aim of the&nbsp;</font></font><font color=\"#443f3f\"><font><i>Transparent\r\nTrade Coffee</i></font></font><font color=\"#443f3f\"><font>&nbsp;program\r\nis to address the issue of appropriate compensation for farmers who\r\ngrow beans for roasters selling into the specialty coffee segment.</font></font></font></font></span></p><br><img src=\"http://i.imgur.com/NovutJV.png\" height=\"520\" width=\"959\"><br><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><font face=\"helvetica\" size=\"4\"><font style=\"color: rgb(68, 63, 63); line-height: 0.25in;\"><font><font>Of\r\ncourse, there is a high-profile precedent for coffee markets\r\ndeveloping ways to let customers to know how farmers are compensated\r\n– the&nbsp;Fair Trade&nbsp;program. However, despite the growing\r\nawareness of&nbsp;Fair Trade&nbsp;coffee, it is surprising how few\r\ncoffee consumers know the actual prices that are paid to the\r\ncooperatives that represent coffee farmers. Under&nbsp;</font></font></font><a href=\"http://www.fairtrade.net/fileadmin/user_upload/content/2009/standards/documents/150311_EN_MainChanges_coffee.pdf\" style=\"line-height: 0.25in;\"><font color=\"#3a3091\"><font>current\r\nrules</font></font></a><font style=\"color: rgb(68, 63, 63); line-height: 0.25in;\" color=\"#443f3f\"><font><font>&nbsp;(updated\r\nin 2011), the&nbsp;Fair Trade&nbsp;price floor for one pound of green\r\ncoffee is $1.40 – plus a $0.20 social premium and another $0.30 if\r\nthe coffee is certified organic. This sums to $1.90 per pound of\r\ncertified Fair Trade Organic (FTO) coffee.</font></font></font></font></p><br><img src=\"http://i.imgur.com/T8xltSI.png\" height=\"875\" width=\"960\"><br><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font style=\"font-size: 10pt\">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n</font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font style=\"font-size: 10pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt;\"><font face=\"helvetica\">Historically\r\n(and importantly), the&nbsp;Fair Trade&nbsp;program has provided\r\ncritical&nbsp;insurance&nbsp;for participating coffee farmers in\r\nmarkets that are dominated by extreme price pressures. The question\r\nthat we are asking is whether it offers appropriate support for\r\nfarmers who participate in specialty markets.&nbsp;After all, how\r\n“fair” is it to pay a farmer $1.90 for coffee that ultimately\r\nsells for, say, $16.00?&nbsp;</font></font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font style=\"font-size: 10pt\">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n</font></span><br></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font style=\"font-size: 10pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt;\"><font face=\"helvetica\">http://www.fairtrade.net/fileadmin/user_upload/content/2009/standards/documents/150311_EN_MainChanges_coffee.pdf</font></font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font style=\"font-size: 10pt\"><font face=\"helvetica\" color=\"#443f3f\"><font color=\"#443f3f\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt;\"><br></font></font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font style=\"font-size: 10pt\"><font face=\"helvetica\" color=\"#443f3f\"><font color=\"#443f3f\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt;\"><br></font></font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font style=\"font-size: 10pt\"><font face=\"helvetica\" color=\"#443f3f\"><font color=\"#443f3f\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt;\"><br></font></font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font style=\"font-size: 10pt\"><font face=\"helvetica\" color=\"#443f3f\"><font color=\"#443f3f\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt;\"><br></font></font></font></font></span></p>','1650842832T8xltSI.png','2014-04-08 07:29:12',9),(9,'Thinking about a Specialty Coffee Retail Price Index','thinking-about-a-specialty-coffee-retail-price-index','	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"color: rgb(68, 63, 63); font-family: helvetica; font-size: 18.6666660308838px;\">What if another benchmark price (not New York \"C\") was allowed to enter into negotiations for green coffee purchases? TT Coffee creates price index that reflects the current prices paid for roasted specialty coffees called the Specialty Coffee Retail Price Index (SCRPI).</span><br></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\"><br></font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"center\"><img src=\"http://transparenttradecoffee.com/app/uploads/blog/1840776886054a02_e6dc7970d909487a8395b7552c3c7375.jpeg_srb_p_500_300_75_22_0.50_1.20_0.00_jpeg_srb.jpg\" width=\"500\"></p>','	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt;\"><font face=\"helvetica\" color=\"#443f3f\">In\r\na previous post, we talked about how important Fair Trade minimum and\r\nNew York “C” prices are to the farmers who grow beans for\r\nspecialty coffee markets. A core problem is that one of these\r\nbenchmark prices is relatively low, while the other is often low and\r\nhighly volatile.</font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"helvetica\">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n</font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font face=\"helvetica\" color=\"#443f3f\">What\r\nif another benchmark price was allowed to enter into negotiations for\r\ngreen coffee purchases; a price index that reflects the current\r\nprices paid for roasted specialty coffees?</font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"helvetica\">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n</font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font face=\"helvetica\" color=\"#443f3f\">To\r\ncreate such an index, we are developing a list of 60 “blue chip”\r\ncoffee roasters; those that set standards in the North American\r\nspecialty coffee market. We are focusing on roasters whose coffees\r\nreceive the lion’s share of attention from Coffee Review, and those\r\nwho receive many of the Good Food Awards and Roast Magazine Awards.\r\nThe roasters that make up the current Specialty Coffee Retail Price\r\nIndex (SCRPI) received about 60% of the more than 1,500 coffee\r\nreviews published up to early 2014, and more than 70% of the Good\r\nFood and Roast Magazine awards during the same period.</font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"helvetica\">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n</font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font face=\"helvetica\" color=\"#443f3f\">The\r\nlist is also balanced in terms of geography, with 10% coming from\r\nCanada and 42% coming from the more coffee-obsessed western United\r\nStates. We are also ensuring that Fair Trade roasters are\r\nappropriately represented. Twenty of the 60 roasters in the current\r\nSCPRI index are listed on the Fair Trade USA or FairTrade Canada\r\nwebsites:</font></font></span></p><div align=\"center\"><img src=\"http://transparenttradecoffee.com/app/uploads/blog/71208734054a02_61582195acf74e3d90ccb3857ef02c22.jpg_srb_p_500_300_75_22_0.50_1.20_0.00_jpg_srb.jpg\" width=\"500\"><br></div><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"center\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\"><img src=\"http://transparenttradecoffee.com/app/uploads/blog/1840776886054a02_e6dc7970d909487a8395b7552c3c7375.jpeg_srb_p_500_300_75_22_0.50_1.20_0.00_jpeg_srb.jpg\" width=\"500\"></font></font></font></span></p><font face=\"helvetica\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt;\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">To\r\ncapture both ends of the specialty coffee market, we visited the\r\nwebsite of each SCRPI roaster in June, 2014 and recorded information\r\nabout their lowest and highest-priced coffees (again, ignoring the\r\nvery high-priced Blue Mountain, Kona, Geisha/Esmeralda and Civet/Kopi\r\nLuwak coffee.<br><br></font></font></span><span style=\"color: rgb(68, 63, 63); font-size: 14pt; line-height: 0.25in;\"></span></font><br><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><font face=\"helvetica\"><span style=\"color: rgb(68, 63, 63); font-size: 14pt; line-height: 0.25in;\">We\r\nthen compared these prices to those recorded in (roughly) December,\r\n2013:</span></font></p><div align=\"center\"><img src=\"http://transparenttradecoffee.com/app/uploads/blog/1792372571054a02_92e5d0ff577e4dddbdaf9f181cb38528.jpeg_srb_p_590_360_75_22_0.50_1.20_0.00_jpeg_srb.jpg\" width=\"590\"></div><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><font face=\"helvetica\"><span style=\"color: rgb(68, 63, 63); font-size: 14pt; line-height: 0.25in;\"><br></span></font></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\" size=\"4\"><font face=\"helvetica\" color=\"#443f3f\"><br></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\" size=\"4\"><font face=\"helvetica\" color=\"#443f3f\">June,\r\n2014 prices at the low end of the specialty coffee market held steady\r\nat $12.01 per 12-ounce bag (down 0.12% from December, 2013). Prices\r\nat the top end of the market declined slightly to $17.23 per 12-ounce\r\nbag (down 2.74% from December, 2013).</font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt;\"><font face=\"helvetica\" color=\"#443f3f\">It\r\nwill be interesting to see what happens when the next set of prices\r\nare pulled in September, 2014. It will be doubly interesting to see\r\nhow this (higher and seemingly stable) price index might become part\r\nof the negotiations for specialty coffee beans grown in future coffee\r\nharvests.</font></font></span></p>\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><br></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><br></p>','1840776886054a02_e6dc7970d909487a8395b7552c3c7375.jpeg_srb_p_500_300_75_22_0.50_1.20_0.00_jpeg_srb.jpg','2014-06-10 07:33:23',8),(10,'Where Does Our Coffee Money Go','where-does-our-coffee-money-go','	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font><font color=\"#443f3f\" size=\"3\">Coffee is crucial to the economies and politics of many developing countries; for many of the world\'s Least Developed Countries. Where does your money go when you purchase coffee? &nbsp;Our team explores.</font></font></font><br></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\"><br></font></font></font></span></p><div align=\"center\"><img src=\"http://transparenttradecoffee.com/app/uploads/blog/2065245282qXWSJrC.jpg\" height=\"350\" width=\"469\"></div>','	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">It\r\nis widely-known that coffee is the second-most traded commodity in\r\nthe world by value (</font></font></font><font color=\"#3a3091\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><u><a href=\"http://www.investorguide.com/article/11836/what-are-the-most-commonly-traded-commodities-igu/\">after\r\noil</a></u></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">).\r\nThis point is made clearly by the&nbsp;</font></font></font><font color=\"#3a3091\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><u><a href=\"http://www.ico.org/coffee_story.asp\">International\r\nCoffee Organization</a></u></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">:</font></font></font></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;</font></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">“<font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\">The\r\nimportance of coffee to the world economy cannot be overstated. It is\r\none of the most valuable primary products in world trade, in many\r\nyears second in value only to oil as a source of foreign exchange to\r\nproducing countries. Its cultivation, processing, trading,\r\ntransportation and marketing provide employment for hundreds of\r\nmillions of people worldwide.&nbsp;</font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><b><font color=\"#443f3f\">Coffee\r\nis crucial to the economies and politics of many developing\r\ncountries; for many of the world\'s Least Developed Countries, exports\r\nof coffee account for more than 50 percent of their foreign exchange\r\nearnings.</font></b></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">”</font></font></font></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;</font></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">Because\r\nof its importance to the people that live and work in the developing\r\nworld, we thought we’d paint a simple but powerful picture of the\r\ngeneral economic conditions in the countries that grow our specialty\r\ncoffees. To do this, we turn to a recently-develo</font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#000000\">ped&nbsp;database&nbsp;</font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">of\r\nNorth American coffee roasters and prices, and to an\r\ninteresting&nbsp;</font></font></font><font color=\"#3a3091\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><u><a href=\"http://www.coffeereview.com/\">website</a></u></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;that\r\nposts a large number of quality reviews for specialty coffees. Here\r\nis a list of the countries that are featured most often in these two\r\ndata sources: <br></font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><br><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"></span></p><img src=\"http://i.imgur.com/qXWSJrC.jpg\" height=\"617\" width=\"961\"><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\"><br></font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\" size=\"4\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">Then,\r\nwe gather some&nbsp;</font></font></font><font color=\"#3a3091\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\" size=\"4\"><u><a href=\"http://data.worldbank.org/indicator/NY.GNP.PCAP.PP.CD\">World\r\nBank data</a></u></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\" size=\"4\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;to\r\ndetermine average per capita income levels for each of these\r\ncountries in 2012. The results are striking.&nbsp;</font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\" size=\"4\"><b><font color=\"#443f3f\">All\r\nspecialty-coffee producing countries (with the exception of the\r\nUnited States) are extremely poor.</font></b></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;</font></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\" size=\"4\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">This\r\nsuggests that as we become comfortable spending more money for the\r\ngreat coffees that are coming from countries like Ethiopia,\r\nIndonesia, Kenya, Colombia, Brazil and Guatemala, we must also ensure\r\nthat more of that money stays in these coffee-producing countries.</font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;</font></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\" size=\"4\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">In\r\nthis spirit, we close this insight with a simple thought experiment.\r\nThe average retail price per 12-ounce bag for the 85 Nicaragua\r\ncoffees in these two databases is $13.56. If we were able to ensure\r\nthat the coffee farmer gets 30% of this price, then her family would\r\nreceive an average of $4.07, which translates into roughly $4.60 per\r\ngreen pound of coffee. This is a $2.70 improvement over&nbsp;</font></font></font><font color=\"#3a3091\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\" size=\"4\"><u><a href=\"http://www.farmersto40.com/blog/2014/4/8/is-fair-trade-really-fair\">current\r\nminimum Fair Trade prices</a></u></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\" size=\"4\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">.\r\nAt this higher price, which is simply appropriate compensation for\r\ngrowing excellent coffee, every 1,000 pounds of specialty coffee that\r\nis grown and then sold in North America would bring an additional\r\n$2,700 into the Nicaragua economy. This increase equals 65% of its\r\ncurrent average GNI per capita.</font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;</font></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\" size=\"4\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">We\r\nare not saying that this is an easy change to make, but it is one\r\npromising way to alleviate the extreme poverty that we are seeing in\r\ncoffee-producing countries around the world.</font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%\" align=\"justify\"><br>\r\n\r\n</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;</font></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%\" align=\"justify\"></p>','2065245282qXWSJrC.jpg','2014-07-21 09:00:06',9),(11,'Bird Rock Roasters - More Transparency Data','bird-rock-roasters-more-transparency-data','	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"left\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">We\r\nhave been analyzing – wherever possible – information about the\r\nshares of posted retail coffee prices that make it back to the\r\nfarmers who grow the beans. Here, we continue these matched analyses\r\nof green and roasted coffee prices by looking at the 2014 Direct\r\nTrade Transparency Report published by Bird Rock Coffee Roasters.</font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"center\"><br><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"></span><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\"><img src=\"http://transparenttradecoffee.com/app/uploads/blog/193816438054a02_72c3406fdee54114848c40868212ab99.png_srb_p_254_182_75_22_0.50_1.20_0.00_png_srb.png\" width=\"254\"></font></font></font></span></p>','<div align=\"center\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\"><img src=\"http://transparenttradecoffee.com/app/uploads/blog/193816438054a02_72c3406fdee54114848c40868212ab99.png_srb_p_254_182_75_22_0.50_1.20_0.00_png_srb.png\" width=\"254\"></font></font></font></span><br></div><br><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">We\r\nhave been analyzing – wherever possible – information about the\r\nshares of posted retail coffee prices that make it back to the\r\nfarmers who grow the beans. Here, we continue these matched analyses\r\nof green and roasted coffee prices by looking at the 2014 Direct\r\nTrade Transparency Report published by Bird Rock Coffee Roasters.&nbsp;</font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\"><br></font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\" size=\"4\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">This\r\nis a detailed and honest account of the economic terms of trade\r\nbetween Bird Rock and its Direct Trade farmers. In it, coffee\r\ndrinkers are reminded that “the price paid to the broker is not the\r\nprice paid to the farmer.&nbsp;The broker’s price includes all\r\nassociated costs of import/export, storage, not to mention the costs\r\nthat broker had to pay to source the coffee at origin in the first\r\nplace on top of the margin that the broker takes — which can be\r\nanywhere from 20 cents a pound to over $1/pound for some brokers.”\r\nThis point is critical because most specialty coffee is sourced\r\nthrough brokers. We are also reminded that “this does not represent\r\na farmer’s profit since there is the cost to grow, harvest and mill\r\nthe coffee.”</font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">Bird\r\nRock’s 2014 Transparency Report provides green coffee price\r\ninformation for fourteen coffees sourced from farms in El Salvador,\r\nGuatemala, Nicaragua and Panama in early 2014. Each price figure\r\nrepresents “the price we paid for the coffee Freight on Board\r\n(FOB), which signifies the price for coffee after milling but before\r\nexport; the final price negotiated with the grower.”</font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n</span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">Our\r\non-line search processes (which rely on the&nbsp;Wayback Machine&nbsp;for\r\ninformation about coffees that are not currently available for sale)\r\nplus email exchanges with Bird Rock owners – turned up matching\r\nretail prices for eleven of these coffees.*&nbsp;After converting\r\nposted retail prices to green-pound equivalents, we are able to\r\ncompare them to their corresponding green coffee prices.**</font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><br><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"></span></p><div align=\"center\"><img src=\"http://transparenttradecoffee.com/app/uploads/blog/484177614054a02_0c562922f7a6458081bd6a68a5b03434.png_srb_p_745_336_75_22_0.50_1.20_0.00_png_srb.png\" width=\"745\"></div><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\"><br></font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\" size=\"4\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">On\r\naverage, Bird Rock’s green coffee prices represent 32.3% of the\r\nretail prices that they charge coffee drinkers. However, this figure\r\nis influenced by a few outliers, including two geisha coffees sourced\r\nfrom Panama at $50 and $55 per green pound! If we look instead at the\r\nmedian share of retail prices going to farmers, we get a figure of\r\n20.9%, which is almost identical to the share reported in a similar\r\nanalysis of Counter Culture’s 2012 Transparency Report.</font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;</font></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\" size=\"4\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">Given\r\nthat these are the (only?) two U.S.-based roasters that go out of\r\ntheir way to post detailed transparency reports that include prices\r\npaid to specific growers on their own websites, it might be fair to\r\nconclude that paying farmers an average of roughly 20% of posted\r\nretail prices represents current best practice in the specialty\r\ncoffee sector. Of course, we will be more certain of this claim as\r\nmore roasters follow the lead of Bird Rock Coffee Roasters and\r\nCounter Culture and tell their customers exactly how much they are\r\npaying their growers for green coffee beans.</font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;</font></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 11pt\" size=\"2\"><i><font color=\"#443f3f\">*\r\nPrices charged to individuals buying coffee in-store may be different\r\nfrom those charged to on-line buyers. To maximize comparability\r\nacross analyses, we only present on-line prices.</font></i></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 11pt\" size=\"2\"><i><font color=\"#443f3f\">**\r\nGreen pound equivalent prices are calculated by converting posted\r\nretail prices to one-pound equivalents and then assuming 15%\r\nshrinkage during the roasting process. In this way, the green pound\r\nequivalent for the Elida Estate coffee from Panama equals $25.99\r\ntimes (16 ounces / 12 ounces) times 85%; or $29.46.</font></i></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">\r\n&nbsp;</font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%\" align=\"justify\"><br>\r\n\r\n</p>','193816438054a02_72c3406fdee54114848c40868212ab99.png_srb_p_254_182_75_22_0.50_1.20_0.00_png_srb.png','2015-03-15 09:06:36',6),(12,'Transparency at Starbucks?','transparency-at-starbucks','	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"color: rgb(20, 24, 35); font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; line-height: 19.3199996948242px; text-align: left;\"><font size=\"3\">Transparent Trade Coffee researchers take a close look at Starbucks’ Coffee and Farmer Equity (C.A.F.E.) program. See how it stacks up.</font></span><br></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"color: rgb(20, 24, 35); font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; line-height: 19.3199996948242px; text-align: left;\"><font size=\"3\"><br></font></span></p><div align=\"center\"><img src=\"http://transparenttradecoffee.com/app/uploads/blog/1234655920YEUOjcA.png\" height=\"659\" width=\"875\"></div>','	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">“<font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\">For\r\ncoffee verified to meet their Coffee and Farmer Equity (C.A.F.E.)\r\nPractices standards, the company says financial transparency “down\r\nto the farmworker level” is a must … [however], the furthest\r\nStarbucks goes in disclosing financial information is to give an\r\naverage purchase price for their green coffee ($2.38 per pound in\r\n2011); they don’t report about individual purchases.”</font></font></font></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;</font></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">This\r\ninconsistency compelled us to look more closely at Starbucks’\r\nsourcing practices. According to Starbucks, transparency is guided by\r\nits Coffee and Farmer Equity (C.A.F.E.) program, which “ensures\r\ncoffee quality while promoting social, economic and environmental\r\nstandards.” Under this model, “economic transparency is required.\r\nSuppliers must submit evidence of payments made throughout the coffee\r\nsupply chain to demonstrate how much of the price that we pay for\r\ngreen coffee gets to the farmer.”</font></font></font></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;</font></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">This\r\nin-house certification program yielded the following summary of their\r\n2014 performance:</font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font color=\"#443f3f\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><img src=\"http://i.imgur.com/1822LQt.png\" height=\"285\" width=\"960\"></font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">Although\r\nthis suggests a small improvement between 2013 and 2014, it does not\r\nreveal how much Starbucks pays for its green coffee. For this, you\r\nhave to dig a little deeper to learn that “Starbucks paid an\r\naverage price of $1.72 per pound in 2014.” According to previous\r\nreports, Starbucks paid an average of $1.92 per pound in 2013, and\r\n$2.56 per pound in 2012. These three numbers, combined with\r\nhistorical information about what Starbucks charged its (on-line)\r\ncustomers for its French, Verona, Sumatra and Pike Place coffees in\r\n2012, 2013 and 2014, generate the following graph: <br></font></font></font></span></p><img src=\"http://i.imgur.com/YEUOjcA.png\" height=\"659\" width=\"962\"><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n</span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">The\r\neffective share of roasted coffee prices that went to purchasing\r\ngreen beans – which probably includes the (unreported) amount that\r\nwent to middlemen – dropped from 23.7% in 2012 to 15.9% in 2014.\r\nGiven the total volume of coffee purchased by Starbucks in 2014 (a\r\nreported 461 million pounds), and this two-year green price reduction\r\nof 84 cents per pound, Starbucks seems to have removed more than $387\r\nmillion from coffee-growing countries over a two year period (unless\r\nthe reported green price reduction came from squeezing the\r\nmiddlemen).</font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\"><br></font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\" size=\"4\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">We\r\nrecognize these numbers and calculations might be incomplete because\r\nwe do not know how much of the money that Starbucks spends on green\r\ncoffee actually goes to growers. This is unfortunate because the\r\nclaims associated with the C.A.F.E. program suggest that these\r\nnumbers are made available by Starbucks’ suppliers – and, we\r\nwould argue, should be disclosed to consumers – for 96% of the\r\ngreen coffee purchased in 2014.</font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">We\r\nalso recognize that the price paid for green beans is not the only\r\nway that roasters support coffee farmers. For example, Starbucks\r\ncontributed $16.3 million in 2014 to support loans to farmers through\r\nRoot Capital (and other partners). However, we should consider that\r\nthe economic value of pre-harvest financing to a farmer is increasing\r\nin the price that he or she gets when the coffee is sold. Thus, to\r\nget a complete picture of these other farm-based programs, we must\r\nsee the more detailed price numbers (and must see them trending in\r\nthe right direction).</font></font></font></span></p>','1234655920YEUOjcA.png','2015-04-06 09:08:45',9),(13,'Specialty Coffee Prices and the Commodity Market','specialty-coffee-prices-and-the-commodity-market','	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"color: rgb(20, 24, 35); font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; line-height: 19.3199996948242px; text-align: left;\"><font size=\"3\">Many roasters have looked for ways to divorce negotiations for green specialty coffee from the volatility that plagues the commodity market. To what extent do cup quality and the prevailing ICO price influence roasted coffee prices? We took a closer look - see what our research team discovered.</font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"></span></p><div align=\"center\"><img src=\"http://transparenttradecoffee.com/app/uploads/blog/8668379177iKSeZn.png\" width=\"872\"></div>','	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">It\r\nis refreshing to hear that a number of roasters are looking for ways\r\nto divorce negotiations for green specialty coffee from the\r\nvolatility that plagues the commodity market.</font></font></font></span></p><img src=\"http://i.imgur.com/urCpPeK.png\" height=\"524\" width=\"960\"><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n</span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">To\r\nstimulate these efforts, we provide some preliminary observations\r\nthat indicate how retail prices for specialty coffees are already\r\ndivorced from this volatility. To do this, we gather the\r\n(refreshingly accessible) price and quality information posted on\r\nthe&nbsp;</font></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><u><a href=\"http://www.coffeereview.com/\">Coffee\r\nReview</a></u></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;website.</font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 11pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">1</font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">Starting\r\nwith coffees that were on the market and reviewed during the 2010 to\r\n2014 period, we set aside what might be called \"elite coffees\"\r\n(i.e., those from Hawaii and Jamaica; the geishas and civet coffees;\r\nand the other coffees that sold for more than $60 per pound). This\r\nleaves 696 coffees that report both retail price and coffee quality\r\ninformation.</font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n</span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">The\r\nfirst thing to note is that these are, on average, excellent coffees;\r\nwith cupping scores averaging 91.5 across the five years.</font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><br><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"></span></p><img src=\"http://i.imgur.com/U62zp0B.png\" height=\"525\" width=\"965\"><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\"><br></font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\" size=\"4\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">Because\r\nthe Coffee Review conducts and posts its reviews monthly, we can\r\nmatch each review in the data to the corresponding monthly average of\r\nthe&nbsp;</font></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\" size=\"4\"><u><a href=\"http://www.ico.org/prices/p2.htm\">ICO\r\nComposite Price</a></u></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\" size=\"4\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">,\r\nwhich captures movements in the global commodity coffee market.</font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 11pt\" size=\"2\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">2</font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\" size=\"4\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;The\r\nsecond figure shows that while retail coffee prices tended to drift\r\nupward over the five-year observation window, the ICO price has been\r\nconsiderably more variable.&nbsp;</font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">The\r\nmore specific question that we tackle here is the extent to which cup\r\nquality and the prevailing ICO price influence roasted coffee prices.\r\nTo do this, we estimate a (very simple) regression model that relates\r\nposted prices per pound to both of these variables.&nbsp;</font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"color: rgb(68, 63, 63); font-size: 14pt; font-family: Helvetica, serif; line-height: 0.25in;\"><br></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"color: rgb(68, 63, 63); font-size: 14pt; font-family: Helvetica, serif; line-height: 0.25in;\">As\r\nyou can see, there is a positive and significant (p=0.00) effect of\r\ncoffee quality on posted prices. In fact, the 0.924 coefficient\r\nestimate suggests that each additional point awarded by the Coffee\r\nReview corresponds with a $0.93 bump in retail price.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%\" align=\"justify\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;</font></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">On\r\nthe other hand,&nbsp;</font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><font color=\"#443f3f\">there\r\nis no discernible effect of the current ICO price on retail coffee\r\nprices</font></i></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">.\r\nThe estimated coefficient (-0.249) is negative, but not statistically\r\nsignificant (p=0.68).</font></font></font></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;</font></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><br></p><img src=\"http://i.imgur.com/5QlRlPo.png\" height=\"415\" width=\"962\">\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">A\r\nlot more can (and should) be done with these kinds of data to ensure\r\nthat the effects presented in this post are robust. For now, however,\r\nit seems safe to assume that prices for roasted specialty coffee are\r\nbeing driven by cup quality (something that growers can influence),\r\nbut are</font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><font color=\"#443f3f\">unaffected\r\nby current commodity price</font></i></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">s.\r\nThus, it makes a lot of sense to liberate coffee growers from the\r\n(unrelated) volatility that plagues the commodity market. &nbsp;</font></font></font></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;</font></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><br></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 0.42in; margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%\" align=\"justify\">\r\n<span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 11pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">1.\r\nThe&nbsp;</font></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 11pt\"><u><a href=\"http://www.coffeereview.com/about-us/\">stated\r\naim</a></u></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 11pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;of\r\nthe Coffee Review is to “entertain and educate coffee drinkers,\r\nfood service professionals, and the coffee trade with a credible and\r\neasy-to-use coffee guide based on objective, blind reviews from\r\nKenneth Davids and other experienced individuals in the specialty\r\ncoffee industry.” Between 1997 and 2014, the Coffee Review\r\nconducted and posted more than 2,000 reviews!</font></font></font></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 0.42in; margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%\" align=\"justify\">\r\n<font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;</font></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 0.42in; margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%\" align=\"justify\">\r\n<span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 11pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">2.\r\nThe International Coffee Organization (ICO) is the main\r\nintergovernmental organization for coffee. It makes a practical\r\ncontribution to the development of a sustainable world coffee sector\r\nand to reducing poverty in developing countries by (among other\r\nthings) “</font></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 11pt\"><u><a href=\"http://www.ico.org/mission07_e.asp?section=About_Us\">promoting\r\nmarket transparency by providing a wide range of statistics on the\r\nworld coffee sector.</a></u></font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%\" align=\"justify\"></p>','8668379177iKSeZn.png','2015-04-22 09:10:51',7),(14,'Counter Culture - Two Years of Transparency Reports','counter-culture-two-years-of-transparency-reports','	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"color: rgb(20, 24, 35); font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; line-height: 19.3199996948242px; text-align: left;\"><font size=\"3\">With a few simple calculations, the data found in Counter Culture\'s transparency reports can be transformed into observations and insights that are critical to understanding the treatment of growers in specialty coffee markets. See what our research team discovered.</font></span><br></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><br><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"></span></p><div align=\"center\"><img src=\"http://transparenttradecoffee.com/app/uploads/blog/560344367uQWAzwA.png\" height=\"429\" width=\"408\"></div>','	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\" size=\"4\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">According\r\nto Roast Magazine’s story,&nbsp;</font></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\" size=\"4\"><u><a href=\"http://www.roastmagazine.com/resources/Articles/Roast_JanFeb13_TheLongPipe.pdf\">The\r\nLong Pipe</a></u></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\" size=\"4\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">,\r\n“</font></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\" size=\"4\"><u><a href=\"https://counterculturecoffee.com/\">Counter\r\nCulture</a></u></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\" size=\"4\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;is\r\none of the only coffee companies in the United States that produces\r\nan annual transparency report—one that curates complex data for\r\ncustomers so that it’s digestible while still being meaningful.”</font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;</font></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\" size=\"4\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">In\r\neach of the past four years, these&nbsp;</font></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\" size=\"4\"><u><a href=\"https://counterculturecoffee.com/sustain/transparency-report\">Transparency\r\nReports</a></u></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\" size=\"4\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;provide\r\nspecific information about the coffees purchased as part of their\r\nDirect Trade program. They report on green coffee prices and cupping\r\nscores, as well as details about the buying relationships between\r\nCounter Culture and its coffee growers.</font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><br><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"></span></p><div align=\"center\"><img src=\"http://i.imgur.com/uQWAzwA.png\" height=\"696\" width=\"661\"></div><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;</font></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\" size=\"4\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">This\r\npost begins with 38 coffees listings found in the 2012 and 2013\r\nTransparency Reports. Using the&nbsp;</font></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\" size=\"4\"><u><a href=\"https://archive.org/\">Internet\r\nArchive</a></u></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\" size=\"4\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">,\r\nwe went “back in time” to locate and match retail sales\r\ninformation to 23 of these coffees (see the table below).</font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;</font></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\" size=\"4\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">On\r\naverage, Counter Culture paid $3.47 per green pound for these\r\ncoffees. At the other end of the specialty coffee value chain, they\r\ncharged their (on-line) customers an average of $18.63 per green\r\npound equivalent. Thus, they returned an average of 18.4% of retail\r\ncoffee prices to their growers. The effective grower shares ranged\r\nfrom 10.5% (Las Milpas in 2013) to 25.9% (Ndaroini in 2012).</font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;</font></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\" size=\"4\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">Because\r\nthese reports provide information on a range of different coffees, we\r\ncan also report some additional summary statistics:</font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;</font></p><span style=\"color: rgb(68, 63, 63); font-size: 14pt; font-family: Helvetica, serif; line-height: 0.25in;\"><ul><li><span style=\"font-size: 14pt; line-height: 0.25in;\">The\r\n	correlation between the green prices and cupping scores is positive\r\n	(?=0.37). This suggests that the growers working with Counter\r\n	Culture are compensated for producing higher coffee quality.&nbsp;</span><br></li><li><span style=\"font-size: 14pt; line-height: 0.25in;\">The\r\n	correlation between green prices and the duration of the\r\n	relationships with Counter Culture is also positive (?=0.41). This\r\n	suggests that growers are rewarded economically for maintaining\r\n	durable trading relationships.</span><br></li></ul></span><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;</font></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\" size=\"4\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">These\r\nobservations indicate the value that comes with presenting just a few\r\ncritical pieces of information – i.e., green coffee prices, cupping\r\nscores and year of first coffee purchase. With a few simple\r\ncalculations, these data can be transformed into observations and\r\ninsights that are critical to understanding the treatment of growers\r\nin specialty coffee markets.</font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><br><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"></span></p><div align=\"center\"><img src=\"http://i.imgur.com/QR7M9z5.png\" width=\"875\"></div><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">We\r\nconclude with one (big?) question. Given the clear commitment to\r\ntransparency and the desire to have customers take these numbers more\r\nseriously, can we effectively present this information to specialty\r\ncoffee consumers&nbsp;</font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><u><font color=\"#443f3f\">when\r\nthey are making their purchase decisions</font></u></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">?</font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\"><br></font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 11pt\" size=\"2\"><i><font color=\"#443f3f\">1.\r\nAs is the case with&nbsp;</font></i></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 11pt\" size=\"2\"><i><u><a href=\"http://www.transparenttradecoffee.org/#!Bird-Rock-Roasters-More-Transparency-Data/cvxy/552207740cf21933cd3bf7b3\">Bird\r\nRock’s Transparency Report</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 11pt\" size=\"2\"><i><font color=\"#443f3f\">,\r\nthese are f.o.b. prices paid to the growers themselves</font></i></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 11pt\"><i><font color=\"#443f3f\">2.\r\nGreen pound equivalent prices are calculated by converting posted\r\nretail prices to one-pound equivalents and then assuming 15%\r\nshrinkage during the roasting process. In this way, the green pound\r\nequivalent for the Concepción Huista coffee equals $15.50 times (16\r\nounces / 12 ounces) times 85%; or $17.57.</font></i></font></font></span></p>','560344367uQWAzwA.png','2015-05-06 09:14:05',9),(15,'Fair Trade Proof Coffee Contracts – 2010 to 2014','fair-trade-proof-coffee-contracts-2010-to-2014','<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><font size=\"3\"><span style=\"color: rgb(20, 24, 35); font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; line-height: 19.3199996948242px;\">Another interesting source of information about prices paid to coffee growers is the Fair Trade Proof website.&nbsp;</span><span style=\"color: rgb(20, 24, 35); font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; line-height: 19.3199996948242px; text-align: left;\">We examine 361 contracts that closed between 2010 and 2014. Find out what the research is telling us</span><span style=\"color: rgb(20, 24, 35); font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; line-height: 19.3199996948242px; text-align: left;\">.</span></font><br></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font color=\"#443f3f\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><br></i></font></font></font></span></p><div align=\"center\"><img src=\"http://transparenttradecoffee.com/app/uploads/blog/650638885iRcqPj9.png\" width=\"157\"></div>','	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">As\r\nwe continue to think about transparency in&nbsp;specialty\r\ncoffee&nbsp;markets, it is important to point to another interesting\r\nsource of information about prices paid to coffee growers.&nbsp;</font></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><u><a href=\"http://www.fairtradeproof.org/\">Fair\r\nTrade Proof</a></u></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">(FTP)\r\nis “a cooperative of independent roasters committed to Fair Trade\r\nas a long-term partnership between farmers and roasters.”</font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><br><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"></span></p><img src=\"http://i.imgur.com/u0BN01z.png\" height=\"463\" width=\"964\">\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;</font></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">A\r\ncritical element of this partnership is a website that houses the\r\ncontracts that document hundreds of specialty coffee transactions.\r\nThe example copied here shows that 17,494 pounds of green coffee were\r\npurchased from&nbsp;</font></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><u><a href=\"http://www.cecocafen.com.ni/\">CECOCAFEN</a></u></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;(a\r\nNicaraguan coffee cooperative) in a contract that closed on February\r\n18, 2014. The price paid for this coffee was $2.21 per pound, which\r\nwas set based on the prevailing NY “C” price, plus premiums for\r\nFair Trade (20 cents), organic (30 cents) and bean quality (20\r\ncents).</font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><br><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"></span></p><img src=\"http://i.imgur.com/MlMqPRc.png\" height=\"475\" width=\"958\"><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n</span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">For\r\nthis post, we compiled data from 361 contracts that closed between\r\n2010 and 2014. These contracts covered coffees produced in 15\r\ncountries by 32 cooperatives, and purchased by 25 different roasters.\r\nThe average contract was for 38,636 pounds of green coffee, and was\r\npriced at $2.78 per pound.</font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><br><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\" size=\"4\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">The\r\nprices in 87% of these contracts were tied explicitly to the NY “C”\r\nprice. Thus, it is not surprising to see that that the year-to-year\r\naverage price in these contracts moves in tandem with the\r\ncorresponding&nbsp;</font></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\" size=\"4\"><u><a href=\"http://www.ico.org/coffee_prices.asp\">ICO\r\nPrice</a></u></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\" size=\"4\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">.\r\nIt is also important to note the consistent positive price\r\ndifferential in these contracts. Overall, they paid an average\r\npremium of $1.17 over the prevailing ICO Price; ranging from $1.00 in\r\n2010 to $1.25 in 2012. <br></font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><br><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"></span></p><div align=\"center\"><img src=\"http://i.imgur.com/VXb8zv5.png\" width=\"875\"><img src=\"http://i.imgur.com/8Igdrsr.png\" width=\"875\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"></span><img src=\"http://i.imgur.com/l6ZQCeE.png\" width=\"875\"><img src=\"http://i.imgur.com/01ov5fq.png\" width=\"875\"></div><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">In\r\na (simple) regression model that relates green prices to the\r\ncurrent-month ICO Price, the parameter estimate is positive and\r\nsignificant. Every $1.00 change in the ICO Price corresponds with a\r\n$1.09 change in prices paid to cooperatives. This is an important\r\ncontrast to the insignificant effect reported in&nbsp;</font></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><u><a href=\"http://www.transparenttradecoffee.org/#!Specialty-Coffee-Prices-and-the-Commodity-Market/cvxy/5537fdf20cf2adc1acde7ac7\">a\r\nmodel that examines the effect of the ICO Price on roasted coffee\r\nprices</a></u></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">.</font></font></font></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;</font></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">Other\r\nparameters in this model suggest that green prices fall slightly as\r\nthe quantity of coffee purchased increases; prices are roughly 0.5\r\ncents per pound lower for every additional 1,000 pounds purchased.</font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><br><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><br></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">On\r\nthe other hand, prices tend to increase with the number of roasters\r\nparticipating in each contract. Moving from one (the minimum) to\r\ntwenty (the maximum) participating roasters corresponds with an\r\naverage price increase of roughly 17.5 cents per pound.</font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n</span><br></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">The\r\ngeographic scope of these contracts tell us something about the\r\naverage prices paid to coffee growers in different countries.\r\nRelative to a small hold-out group that consists of coffees from\r\nBrazil, Dominican Republic, DR Congo, Ecuador and El Salvador there\r\nis a significant “Colombia premium” of 20.1 cents per pound, an\r\n“Indonesia premium” of 29.2 cents per pound, and an “Ethiopia\r\npremium” of 67.6 cents per pound. There is also a significant\r\n“Honduras discount” of 28.7 cents per pound, a “Nicaragua\r\ndiscount” of 23.0 cents per pound, and a “Peru discount” of\r\n17.1 cents per pound.</font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n</span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">We\r\nclose this post with a request to FTP roasters. With a fair bit of\r\neffort, we were able to locate the web pages where 84 of the roasted\r\ncoffees covered by 2014 FTP contracts are sold. This allows us to\r\ntell the potential consumers of each coffee the green price paid and\r\nthe corresponding effective share of retail price going to the\r\ngrower. The final table in this post indicates that FTP roasters paid\r\nan average of $2.89 per green pound for these coffees, which\r\ntranslates into an average effective grower share of 22.9%.\r\nIndividually, our research suggests that:</font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\"><br></font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n</span></p><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><ul style=\"font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\"><li><font style=\"font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\" face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">Cafe\r\n	Campesino’s&nbsp;</font></font></font><font style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\" color=\"#0000ff\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><u><a href=\"http://www.cafecampesino.com/Bolivia_Medium_Roast_Coffee_p/c106.htm\">Bolivia\r\n	Medium Roast Coffee</a></u></font></font></font><font style=\"font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\" face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;was\r\n	sourced from Bolivia – FECAFEB at $2.71 per green pound. The\r\n	roasted coffee sells for $12.95 per pound, which translates into an\r\n	effective grower share of 24.6%;</font></font></font><br></li><li><font style=\"font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\" face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">Higher\r\n	Grounds’&nbsp;</font></font></font><font style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\" color=\"#0000ff\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><u><a href=\"http://www.highergroundstrading.com/cart/34/coffee/single-origin-coffees/organic-mexican-yachil-dark-roast\">Organic\r\n	Mexican Yachil Dark Roast</a></u></font></font></font><font style=\"font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\" face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;was\r\n	sourced from Mexico – Yachil at $2.74 per green pound. The roasted\r\n	coffee sells for $11.00 per 12-ounce bag, which translates into an\r\n	effective grower share of 21.9%; and</font></font></font></li><li><font style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in; color: rgb(68, 63, 63);\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">Just\r\n	Coffee’s&nbsp;</font></font></font><font style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\" color=\"#0000ff\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><u><a href=\"http://shop.justcoffee.coop/collections/single-origin/products/sumatra-light-roasted-single-origin\">Light\r\n	Sumatra</a></u></font></font></font><font style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in; color: rgb(68, 63, 63);\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;was\r\n	sourced from Indonesia - APKO/Askogo/Permata Gayo at $2.93 per green\r\n	pound. The roasted coffee sells for $14.00 per 12-ounce bag, which\r\n	translates into an effective grower share of 18.4%.</font></font></font></li></ul></font>\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">It\r\nwould be great to see these details confirmed and then posted to\r\nthe&nbsp;</font></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><u><a href=\"http://www.transparenttradecoffee.org/#!ttcoffees/cjg9\">TT\r\nCoffees page</a></u></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;on\r\nthis site!</font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n</span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 11pt\"><i><font color=\"#443f3f\">*\r\nGreen pound equivalent (GPE) retail prices are calculated by\r\nconverting posted prices to one-pound equivalents and then assuming\r\n15% shrinkage during the roasting process. In this way, the green\r\npound equivalent for the Colombia - Fondo Paez coffee from Amavida\r\nCoffee equals $14.50 times (16 ounces / 12 ounces) times 85%; or\r\n$16.43.</font></i></font></font></span></p>','650638885iRcqPj9.png','2015-05-19 09:16:56',7),(17,'Cup of Excellence – Five Years of Competition and Auction Data','cup-of-excellence-five-years-of-competition-and-auction-data','	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><font size=\"3\"><span style=\"color: rgb(20, 24, 35); font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; line-height: 19.3199996948242px; text-align: left;\">Do markets work better for growers when real competition is introduced? We explored this question by analyzing five years of competition and auction data from&nbsp;</span><a class=\"profileLink\" href=\"https://www.facebook.com/CupOfExcellence\" data-hovercard=\"/ajax/hovercard/page.php?id=53803923418\" saprocessedanchor=\"true\" aria-owns=\"js_1t\" aria-haspopup=\"true\" aria-describedby=\"js_1u\" id=\"js_1v\" style=\"color: rgb(59, 89, 152); cursor: pointer; font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; line-height: 19.3199996948242px; text-align: left;\">Cup Of Excellence</a><span style=\"color: rgb(20, 24, 35); font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; line-height: 19.3199996948242px; text-align: left;\">&nbsp;(COE). Find out what the research is telling us.</span></font><br></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><br><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"></span></p><div align=\"center\"><img src=\"http://transparenttradecoffee.com/app/uploads/blog/995864146aJTUARo.png\" width=\"295\"></div>','	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font color=\"#0000ff\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><u><a href=\"https://www.allianceforcoffeeexcellence.org/en/cup-of-excellence/\">Cup\r\nof Excellence</a></u></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;(COE)\r\nprograms have been run in ten coffee-growing countries since as early\r\nas 1999. In these programs, many of the country’s top coffee\r\ngrowers compete for the attention and affirmation of the world’s\r\nmost discerning coffee tasters. After cuppings are completed, winning\r\ncoffees (roughly 25 per competition, on average) are auctioned off to\r\nglobal buyers that gather at each event.</font></font></font></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;</font></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">Thanks\r\nto COE organizers’ commitment to transparency, we can see that the\r\naverage price per green pound paid at auction rose from $4.09 in 2005\r\nto $9.56 in 2014. We can also see how year-to-year movements in\r\naverage auction prices trace the average quality scores received at\r\nthe competitions. Winning bids were highest in 2013 ($10.03 per\r\npound), when the average cupping score was 87.5. Lower prices were\r\nobserved in 2011 ($7.23 per pound) when the average cupping score was\r\n86.6.</font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><br><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"></span></p><div align=\"center\"><img src=\"http://i.imgur.com/3gX0qyT.png\" width=\"719\"></div><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"color: rgb(68, 63, 63); font-size: 14pt; font-family: Helvetica, serif; line-height: 100%;\"><br></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"color: rgb(68, 63, 63); font-size: 14pt; font-family: Helvetica, serif; line-height: 100%;\">Country\r\nEffects</span></p>\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\"><br></font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">When\r\nwe hone in on the last five years of the program – 2010 to 2014 –\r\nit is not as clear that auction prices always track cupping scores at\r\nthe country level. Over this period, auction prices were highest in\r\nGuatemala ($10.72 per pound), which had the lowest average cupping\r\nscore (86.8). At the other extreme, prices in Brazilian and\r\nNicaraguan auctions were quite low ($7.72 and $7.58 per pound)\r\ndespite high average cupping scores (87.5 and 87.4).</font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><br><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"></span></p><div align=\"center\"><img src=\"http://i.imgur.com/jZEZkDT.png\" width=\"683\"></div><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\" size=\"4\"><font color=\"#443f3f\"><br></font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\" size=\"4\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">A\r\nSimple Regression Model</font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">We\r\nuse these same five years of data to estimate a simple regression\r\nmodel that shows the country-of-origin effects, as well as an\r\nexpected trade-off between lot size (i.e., quantity) and price. For\r\nevery additional bag of coffee offered at auction, the winning bid\r\nfalls by an average of roughly 6.6 cents per pound.&nbsp;</font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\" size=\"4\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">The\r\nmodel also shows the positive and significant effect of cupping\r\nscores on prices. On average, each additional point awarded by\r\ncompetition judges corresponds with a $0.76 bump in the winning\r\nauction bid. However, auction participants are not only bidding on\r\ncoffee quality, but also competition rank. The rank coefficients in\r\nthe model suggest that winning coffees sold for an average premium of\r\n$17.43 per pound! Even fifth-ranked coffees sold for a modest price\r\npremium of $1.24 per pound.</font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;</font></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\" size=\"4\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">Another\r\nvariable in the model counts the number of prior COE events held in\r\neach country. The positive coefficient on this variable suggests that\r\n– all else equal – auction prices increase by roughly 15.5 cents\r\nevery time another COE competition is held in the country. <br></font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><br><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"></span></p><div align=\"center\"><img src=\"http://i.imgur.com/OH6ZPqx.png\" width=\"875\"></div><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;</font></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\" size=\"4\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">Finally,\r\nbecause we know the month and year of each COE auction, we can match\r\nevery observation with the corresponding monthly average of the&nbsp;</font></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\" size=\"4\"><u><a href=\"http://www.ico.org/prices/p2.htm\">ICO\r\nComposite Price</a></u></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\" size=\"4\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">,\r\nwhich captures movements in the global commodity coffee market.&nbsp;\r\nThe model returns a&nbsp;</font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\" size=\"4\"><u><font color=\"#443f3f\">negative</font></u></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\" size=\"4\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;ICO\r\nPrice coefficient. Unlike the positive effect observed in&nbsp;</font></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\" size=\"4\"><u><a href=\"http://www.transparenttradecoffee.org/#!Fair-Trade-Proof-Coffee-Contracts-%E2%80%93-2010-to-2014/cvxy/555bb6580cf298b2d3ccf79a\">a\r\nprevious analysis of Fair Trade Proof data</a></u></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\" size=\"4\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">,\r\nCOE auction prices tend to run counter-cyclically with commodity\r\ncoffee prices.</font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;</font></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\" size=\"4\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">What\r\nCould All of this Mean?</font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\">\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">These\r\nobservations seem to suggest that green coffee markets can work\r\nfairly well when real competition is introduced into the buying\r\nprocess. Quality is rewarded and prices trend upward as competition\r\nintensifies. However, several questions require further thought and\r\nmore analysis. For example:&nbsp;</font></font></font></span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\"><br></font></font></font></span></p><ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\">\r\n	<span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">Why\r\n	are we seeing large average country differences in auction prices,\r\n	even after controlling for coffee quality? &nbsp;</font></font></font></span></p>\r\n	</li><li>\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\">\r\n	<span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">What\r\n	about the rest of the specialty coffee being produced each year, and\r\n	the coffee growers not featured in the COE auctions? After all, all\r\n	of the 2010 to 2014 COE auctions combined featured just 1,170 coffee\r\n	growers and 45,000 sacks of coffee.</font></font></font></span></p>\r\n	</li><li>\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\">\r\n	<span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">For\r\n	these coffees and these growers, how can we restructure specialty\r\n	coffee markets so that quality-based competition drives all green\r\n	coffee negotiations toward prices fetched in COE auctions, as\r\n	opposed to the lower and highly-variable commodity prices?</font></font></font></span></p>\r\n</li></ul>\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">(One\r\nmight also ask what happens to the top-ranked COE coffees when they\r\nhit the retail market … we’ll look at these prices in a future\r\npost. Stay tuned to&nbsp;</font></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><u><a href=\"http://www.transparenttradecoffee.org/\">www.transparenttradecoffee.org</a></u></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">.)</font></font></font></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;</font></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;</font></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 11pt\"><i><font color=\"#443f3f\">1.\r\nThese competition rank effects are consistent with those reported\r\nby&nbsp;</font></i></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 11pt\"><i><u><a href=\"http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/agec.12132/abstract\">Wilson\r\nand Wilson</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 11pt\"><i><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;in\r\ntheir analysis of data covering the 2004 to 2010 period.</font></i></font></font></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\" align=\"justify\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;</font></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%\" align=\"justify\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 11pt\"><i><font color=\"#443f3f\">2.\r\nThe International Coffee Organization (ICO) is the main\r\nintergovernmental organization for coffee. It makes a practical\r\ncontribution to the development of a sustainable world coffee sector\r\nand to reducing poverty in developing countries by (among other\r\nthings) “</font></i></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 11pt\"><i><u><a href=\"http://www.ico.org/mission07_e.asp?section=About_Us\">promoting\r\nmarket transparency by providing a wide range of statistics on the\r\nworld coffee sector</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 11pt\"><i><font color=\"#443f3f\">.”</font></i></font></font></span></p>','995864146aJTUARo.png','2015-06-03 09:39:49',9),(18,'Talking About Transparency','talking-about-transparency','	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n<p align=\"justify\" style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\"><font size=\"3\"><span style=\"color: rgb(20, 24, 35); font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; line-height: 19.3199996948242px; text-align: left;\">The TT Coffee T</span><span style=\"color: rgb(20, 24, 35); font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; line-height: 19.3199996948242px; text-align: left;\">eam takes a closer look at how 26 SCRPI Roasters talk about pricing transparency on their websites. Our latest Insight puts structure around these 26 transparency statements and provides click through links to give you a better idea about the context of each statement.</span></font><br></p><p align=\"justify\" style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\"><font size=\"3\"><span style=\"color: rgb(20, 24, 35); font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; line-height: 19.3199996948242px; text-align: left;\"><br></span></font></p><p align=\"justify\" style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\"><img src=\"http://transparenttradecoffee.com/app/uploads/blog/462072294TT_TalkingT26.png\" width=\"962\"><font size=\"3\"><span style=\"color: rgb(20, 24, 35); font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; line-height: 19.3199996948242px; text-align: left;\"><br></span></font></p>','	\r\n	\r\n	\r\n\r\n\r\n<p align=\"justify\" style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font color=\"#0000ff\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><u><a href=\"http://www.transparenttradecoffee.org/\">Transparent\r\nTrade Coffee</a></u></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;(TTC)&nbsp;is\r\nworking to change specialty coffee market conversations and, in doing\r\nso, improve economic outcomes for coffee growers. We are doing this\r\nby emphasizing pricing transparency; anchoring all specialty coffee\r\nconversations on the prices paid to growers for their green coffee.</font></font></font></span></p>\r\n<p align=\"justify\" style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;</font></p>\r\n<p align=\"justify\" style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">We\r\nare clearly not the first to talk about transparency. To provide a\r\nfeel for how different roasters are talking about pricing\r\ntransparency, we searched the websites of the&nbsp;</font></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><u><a href=\"http://www.transparenttradecoffee.org/#!roasters/clar\">SCRPI\r\nRoasters</a></u></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;and\r\nlocated sentences that include the words ‘transparent’ or\r\n‘transparency.’</font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 8pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">1</font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;In\r\nthe end, we found references to pricing transparency on the websites\r\nof 26 of the SCRPI Roasters.&nbsp;</font></font></font></span></p>\r\n<p align=\"justify\" style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;</font></p>\r\n<p align=\"justify\" style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">To\r\nget a feel for what roasters are talking about when they talk\r\ntransparency, we invite readers to read through the following\r\nstructured presentation of these transparency statements, and to\r\nclick through each of the hyperlinks to get a better idea about the\r\ncontext of each statement.</font></font></font></span></p>\r\n<p align=\"justify\" style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;</font></p>\r\n<p align=\"justify\" style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">Some\r\nroasters offer fairly basic statements about transparency:</font></font></font></span></p><p align=\"justify\" style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\"><br></font></font></font></span></p>\r\n<font color=\"#443f3f\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\"><ul><li><font color=\"#443f3f\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\">“<font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i>Additionally,\r\n	public demand continues to increase for coffee that is ethical\r\n	and&nbsp;transparentto the source.” (</i></font></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><u><a href=\"http://www.1000facescoffee.com/blog/2014/12/14/coloring-in-the-wild\">1000\r\n	Faces Coffee</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\" style=\"font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><font color=\"#443f3f\">)</font></i></font></font><br></li><li><font color=\"#443f3f\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\">“<font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i>In\r\n	addition to this&nbsp;transparency&nbsp;in price discovery we\r\n	sometimes pre-finance a producer ahead of the harvest.” (</i></font></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><u><a href=\"http://batdorfcoffee.com/blog/coffee/what-is-relationship-coffee/\">Batdorf\r\n	&amp; Bronson</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\" style=\"font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><font color=\"#443f3f\">)</font></i></font></font><br></li><li><font color=\"#443f3f\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\">“<font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i>In\r\n	the last decade or two we’ve seen the emergence of what has been\r\n	called the Third Wave of coffee – a loosely defined movement\r\n	toward higher quality drinks, more differentiation\r\n	andtransparency&nbsp;around coffee as a seasonal product, and a\r\n	general reverence for many aspects of the craft.” (</i></font></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><u><a href=\"https://bluebottlecoffee.com/frequency/except-for-espresso\">Blue\r\n	Bottle Coffee</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\" style=\"font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><font color=\"#443f3f\">)</font></i></font></font><br></li><li><font color=\"#443f3f\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\">“<font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i>De\r\n	La Paz isn’t the first coffee roaster in the world to focus\r\n	on&nbsp;transparent&nbsp;and seasonal blends.” (</i></font></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><u><a href=\"https://www.delapazcoffee.com/about/\">De\r\n	La Paz Coffee</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\" style=\"font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><font color=\"#443f3f\">)</font></i></font></font><br></li><li><font color=\"#443f3f\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\">“<font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i>The\r\n	currency of leadership is truth and&nbsp;transparency.”\r\n	(</i></font></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><u><a href=\"https://www.news.starbucks.com/2014annualmeeting/howard-schultz-2014-shareholders-speech\">Starbucks</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\" style=\"font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><font color=\"#443f3f\">)</font></i></font></font><br></li><li><font color=\"#443f3f\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\">“<font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i>The\r\n	results of all this discussion and technology, as so many other\r\n	industries have experienced, are&nbsp;transparency&nbsp;and\r\n	traceability.” (</i></font></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><u><a href=\"http://www.zokacoffee.com/the_third_wave_in_its_third_year/\">Zoka\r\n	Coffee Roasters</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\" style=\"font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><font color=\"#443f3f\">)</font></i></font></font><br></li></ul></font>\r\n<p align=\"justify\" style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;</font></p>\r\n<p align=\"justify\" style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">Other\r\nroasters articulate the challenges associated with pricing\r\ntransparency:</font></font></font></span></p><p align=\"justify\" style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\"><br></font></font></font></span></p>\r\n<span style=\"color: rgb(68, 63, 63); font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\"><ul><li><span style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\">“</span><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\" style=\"font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i>Coffee\r\n	can change hands multiple times between the producer and the\r\n	consumer, makingtransparency&nbsp;difficult.” (Caribou Coffee)</i></font></font><br></li><li><font color=\"#443f3f\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\">“<font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i>Roasters\r\n	seeking&nbsp;transparency&nbsp;regarding farming practices, farmer\r\n	income, and living standards must work extra hard to obtain\r\n	information and develop relationships on the ground.” (</i></font></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><u><a href=\"http://www.equatorcoffees.com/our-story\">Equator\r\n	Estate Coffees &amp; Teas</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\" style=\"font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><font color=\"#443f3f\">)</font></i></font></font><br></li></ul></span>\r\n<p align=\"justify\" style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;</font></p>\r\n<p align=\"justify\" style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">Many\r\nroasters mention transparency as a requirement for Fair Trade (and\r\nother) certifications:</font></font></font></span></p><p align=\"justify\" style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\"><br></font></font></font></span></p>\r\n<font color=\"#443f3f\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\"><ul><li><font color=\"#443f3f\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\">“<font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i>Democratic\r\n	and&nbsp;transparent&nbsp;organizations.” (</i></font></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><u><a href=\"http://www.allegrocoffee.com/about/our-story/our-story#faq\">Allegro\r\n	Coffee</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\" style=\"font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><font color=\"#443f3f\">)\r\n	(</font></i></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><u><a href=\"https://www.armeno.com/store/coffees.aspx\">Armeno\r\n	Coffee</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\" style=\"font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><font color=\"#443f3f\">)</font></i></font></font><br></li><li><font color=\"#443f3f\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\">“<font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i>Certification\r\n	is one primary vehicle for accountability, assurance\r\n	and&nbsp;transparency.” (</i></font></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><u><a href=\"https://www.alpensierracoffee.com/blog/sustainable-coffee-certified-or-not/\">Alpen\r\n	Sierra</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\" style=\"font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><font color=\"#443f3f\">)</font></i></font></font><br></li><li><font color=\"#443f3f\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\">“<font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i>In\r\n	2008, we launched our third-party certified Counter Culture Direct\r\n	Trade Certification, which established direct trade standards for\r\n	sustainability, fairness, quality, andtransparency&nbsp;in the\r\n	coffee chain.” (</i></font></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><u><a href=\"https://counterculturecoffee.com/contact/about-us\">Counter\r\n	Culture</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\" style=\"font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><font color=\"#443f3f\">)</font></i></font></font><br></li><li><font color=\"#443f3f\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\">“<font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i>The\r\n	certification process required us to answer a series of questions\r\n	that demonstratetransparency&nbsp;and accountability in our\r\n	financial records and supply chain, and consideration of workers,\r\n	the community, and the environment in our decision making.”\r\n	(</i></font></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><u><a href=\"http://www.equatorcoffees.com/our-story\">Equator\r\n	Estate Coffees &amp; Teas</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\" style=\"font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><font color=\"#443f3f\">)</font></i></font></font><br></li><li><font color=\"#443f3f\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\">“<font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i>C.A.F.E.\r\n	Practices includes guidelines in four key areas: quality, economic\r\n	accountability and&nbsp;transparency, social responsibility and\r\n	environmental leadership. Economictransparency&nbsp;is required.”\r\n	(</i></font></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><u><a href=\"http://www.starbucks.com/responsibility/sourcing/coffee\">Starbucks</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\" style=\"font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><font color=\"#443f3f\">)</font></i></font></font><br></li></ul></font>\r\n<p align=\"justify\" style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;</font></p>\r\n<p align=\"justify\" style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">One\r\nroaster flips this switch and mentions transparency in a critique of\r\nFair Trade:</font></font></font></span></p><p align=\"justify\" style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\"><br></font></font></font></span></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n<p align=\"justify\" style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\">\r\n	<span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">“<font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i>Another\r\n	flaw of fair trade is its lack of&nbsp;transparency.” (</i></font></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><u><a href=\"https://www.theroasterie.com/blog/does-fair-trade-coffee-hold-up-to-its-name/\">The\r\n	Roasterie</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><font color=\"#443f3f\">)</font></i></font></font></span></p>\r\n</li></ul>\r\n<p align=\"justify\" style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;</font></p>\r\n<p align=\"justify\" style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">For\r\na few roasters, transparency is built into the requirements for\r\nwinning a&nbsp;</font></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><u><a href=\"http://www.goodfoodawards.org/coffee/\">Good\r\nFood Award</a></u></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">:</font></font></font></span></p><p align=\"justify\" style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\"><br></font></font></font></span></p>\r\n<font color=\"#443f3f\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\"><ul><li><font color=\"#443f3f\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\">“<font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i>To\r\n	qualify for entry, roasters and coffee farmers must emphasize\r\n	fairness and&nbsp;transparencyfrom seed to cup, and be using third\r\n	party certified organic beans.” (</i></font></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><u><a href=\"http://www.49thparallelroasters.com/blogs/news/4351962-organic-coffees\">49th\r\n	Parallel Coffee Roasters</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\" style=\"font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><font color=\"#443f3f\">)</font></i></font></font><br></li><li><font color=\"#443f3f\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\">“<font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i>Finalists\r\n	attested to responsible production by detailing their efforts to\r\n	eliminate or reduce pesticides, herbicides and chemical fertilizers,\r\n	source ingredients locally where possible, implement water and\r\n	energy conservation, ensure traceability to the farm level, practice\r\n	good animal husbandry and exercise fair and&nbsp;transparent&nbsp;treatment\r\n	of workers and suppliers.” (</i></font></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><u><a href=\"http://www.evansbrotherscoffee.com/blog/evans-brothers-coffee-named-a-winner-of-prestigious-good-food-awards\">Evans\r\n	Brothers Coffee Roasters</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\" style=\"font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><font color=\"#443f3f\">)</font></i></font></font><br></li><li><font color=\"#443f3f\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\">“<font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i>In\r\n	addition to the results of the cupping, in order for coffees to\r\n	qualify for the award, the producers and roasters needed to\r\n	emphasize fairness and&nbsp;transparency&nbsp;from seed to cup.”\r\n	(</i></font></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><u><a href=\"http://www.ptscoffee.com/90-coffee-reviews/we-are-good-food-awards-finalists\">PT\'s\r\n	Coffee Roasting Co.</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\" style=\"font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><font color=\"#443f3f\">)</font></i></font></font><br></li></ul></font>\r\n<p align=\"justify\" style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;</font></p>\r\n<p align=\"justify\" style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">However,\r\nmost of the conversation around pricing transparency emphasizes its\r\nrole in the relationships that are part of a growing Direct Trade\r\ncoffee movement:&nbsp;</font></font></font></span></p><p align=\"justify\" style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\"><br></font></font></font></span></p>\r\n<font color=\"#443f3f\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\"><ul><li><font color=\"#443f3f\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\">“<font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i>Barefoot\r\n	is able to source high quality coffee that is indicative of the\r\n	region and terroir, and you the customer can take part in helping to\r\n	empower these farmers to become self sufficient and strengthen the\r\n	ties of&nbsp;transparency.” (</i></font></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><u><a href=\"http://www.barefootcoffee.com/products/yirgacheffe-kochere\">Barefoot\r\n	Coffee Roasters</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\" style=\"font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><font color=\"#443f3f\">)</font></i></font></font><br></li><li><font color=\"#443f3f\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\">“<font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i>We\r\n	not only strive to develop relationships with the farmers to ensure\r\n	full&nbsp;transparency&nbsp;of the buying process, but these\r\n	relationships allow us to provide important feedback to the farmers\r\n	to let them know when they are producing a great crop of coffee.”\r\n	(</i></font></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><u><a href=\"http://birdrockcoffee.com/philosophy/\">Bird\r\n	Rock Coffee Roasters</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\" style=\"font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><font color=\"#443f3f\">)</font></i></font></font><br></li><li><font color=\"#443f3f\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\">“<font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i>We\r\n	work hard developing relationships in the sourcing process and we\r\n	offer absolutetransparency&nbsp;on each of our storied coffees.”\r\n	(</i></font></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><u><a href=\"http://cqcoffeeroasters.com/pages/our-prime-directive\">CQ\r\n	Coffee Roasters</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\" style=\"font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><font color=\"#443f3f\">)</font></i></font></font><br></li><li><font color=\"#443f3f\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\">“<font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i>We\r\n	strive for&nbsp;transparency&nbsp;in our coffee sourcing and have\r\n	developed strong relationships with the importers, co-ops and\r\n	farmers from whom we buy coffee.” (</i></font></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><u><a href=\"https://victrolacoffeeroasters.wordpress.com/page/2/\">Victrola\r\n	Coffee Roasters</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\" style=\"font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><font color=\"#443f3f\">)</font></i></font></font><br></li></ul></font>\r\n<p align=\"justify\" style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;</font></p>\r\n<p align=\"justify\" style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">And,\r\nspecifically, its implications for delivering better prices that\r\nreward coffee growers for their investments in quality:</font></font></font></span></p>\r\n<font color=\"#443f3f\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\"><ul><li><font color=\"#443f3f\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\">“<font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i>The\r\n	premise is simple: Engage producers in the quality process, control\r\n	quality from tree to port, make it all transparent, and&nbsp;</i></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\" style=\"font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><u><font color=\"#443f3f\">pay\r\n	prices that reward outstanding results</font></u></i></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\" style=\"font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><font color=\"#443f3f\">.\r\n	Ourtransparency&nbsp;contract is an important tool that defines and\r\n	documents costs and profit across the chain of custody.”\r\n	(</font></i></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><u><a href=\"http://www.intelligentsiacoffee.com/content/coffee-process\">Intelligentsia\r\n	Coffee</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\" style=\"font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><font color=\"#443f3f\">)</font></i></font></font><br></li><li><font color=\"#443f3f\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\">“<font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i>We\r\n	seek to deliver the&nbsp;</i></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\" style=\"font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><u><font color=\"#443f3f\">highest\r\n	possible return to farmers</font></u></i></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\" style=\"font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;and\r\n	therefore, whenever possible, require our importers, exporters,\r\n	cooperatives and farmers to agree upon the financial distribution\r\n	prior to harvest and act&nbsp;transparently&nbsp;in the execution of\r\n	distribution, allowing us to monitor the committed delivery price to\r\n	the farmers. Open&nbsp;transparency&nbsp;is critical, therefore we\r\n	work with all participants in the chain to provide full disclosure\r\n	back to the farmer or cooperative.” (</font></i></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><u><a href=\"http://www.klatchroasting.com/Direct_Trade_Coffee_s/42.htm\">Klatch\r\n	Coffee</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\" style=\"font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><font color=\"#443f3f\">)</font></i></font></font><br></li><li><font color=\"#443f3f\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\">“<font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i>We\r\n	seek to deliver the&nbsp;</i></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\" style=\"font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><u><font color=\"#443f3f\">highest\r\n	possible return to farmers</font></u></i></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\" style=\"font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;and\r\n	require our importers, exporters, cooperatives and farmers to agree\r\n	upon the financial distribution prior to harvest and\r\n	act&nbsp;transparently&nbsp;in the execution of distribution,\r\n	allowing us to monitor the committed delivery price to the farmers.\r\n	All Direct Trade participants must be open to&nbsp;transparentdisclosure\r\n	of financial deliveries back to the individual farmers.” (</font></i></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><u><a href=\"http://www.ptscoffee.com/learn/direct-trade-coffee\">PT\'s\r\n	Coffee Roasting Co.</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\" style=\"font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><font color=\"#443f3f\">)</font></i></font></font><br></li><li><font color=\"#443f3f\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\">“<font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i>While\r\n	there is no stamp or logo to differentiate a direct trade coffee in\r\n	the market, there is traceability,&nbsp;transparency, and quality.\r\n	This&nbsp;transparency&nbsp;secures a&nbsp;</i></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\" style=\"font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><u><font color=\"#443f3f\">fair\r\n	price for the farmer</font></u></i></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\" style=\"font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><font color=\"#443f3f\">and\r\n	a quality product for the consumer.” (</font></i></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><u><a href=\"https://www.theroasterie.com/blog/responsible-coffee-usda-organic-vs-fair-trade-vs-direct-trade/\">The\r\n	Roasterie</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\" style=\"font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><font color=\"#443f3f\">)</font></i></font></font><br></li><li><font color=\"#443f3f\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\">“<font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i>Direct\r\n	Trade is predicated on a few simple pillars: improving coffee\r\n	quality,&nbsp;</i></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\" style=\"font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><u><font color=\"#443f3f\">incentive\r\n	based rewards</font></u></i></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\" style=\"font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;to\r\n	the farmer and&nbsp;transparency&nbsp;of the supply chain.”\r\n	(</font></i></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><u><a href=\"http://stumptowncoffee.com/education-overview/direct-trade/\">Stumptown\r\n	Coffee Roasters</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\" style=\"font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><font color=\"#443f3f\">)</font></i></font></font><br></li><li><font color=\"#443f3f\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\">“<font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i>In\r\n	order to ensure the highest quality cup, and build truly sustainable\r\n	sourcing, we make partners and friends throughout the supply chain\r\n	so that we control quality in every step of coffee travel,&nbsp;</i></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\" style=\"font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><u><font color=\"#443f3f\">set\r\n	payment&nbsp;</font></u></i></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\" style=\"font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><font color=\"#443f3f\">in\r\n	a&nbsp;transparent&nbsp;way, reach out to communities around the\r\n	world, and ensure a high standard of farming practices.” (</font></i></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><u><a href=\"http://templecoffee.com/farm-to-cup-sourcing/\">Temple\r\n	Coffee and Tea</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\" style=\"font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><font color=\"#443f3f\">)</font></i></font></font><br></li><li><font color=\"#443f3f\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\">“</font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\" style=\"font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><u><font color=\"#443f3f\">Paying\r\n	a fair wage</font></u></i></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\" style=\"font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;for\r\n	high quality coffees is just one of the ways we\r\n	establish&nbsp;transparentrelationships based on trust and mutual\r\n	respect and allows coffee drinkers and coffee farmers to connect\r\n	with every cup.” (</font></i></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><u><a href=\"http://www.thanksgivingcoffee.com/fairtrade\">Thanksgiving\r\n	Coffee</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\" style=\"font-size: 1rem; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); line-height: 0.25in;\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><font color=\"#443f3f\">)</font></i></font></font><br></li></ul></font>\r\n<p align=\"justify\" style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;</font></p>\r\n<p align=\"justify\" style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">The\r\nfollowing sentence succinctly captures a critical motivation of the\r\nTTC movement by stressing how transparency improves growers’\r\nleverage and frees green coffee negotiations from the harmful\r\nvolatility observed in commodity coffee markets:</font></font></font></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p align=\"justify\" style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\"></p><ul><li><font color=\"#443f3f\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in; color: rgb(68, 63, 63);\">“<font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i>The\r\n	trading process is&nbsp;transparent; farmers gain bargaining power\r\n	through knowledge, and receive a fair price that is not vulnerable\r\n	to commodity market fluctuations.” (</i></font></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><u><a href=\"http://www.gimmecoffee.com/news/what-relationship-coffee#sthash.53gDkmaV.dpbs\">Gimme!\r\n	Coffee</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\" style=\"font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><font color=\"#443f3f\">)</font></i></font></font><span style=\"color: rgb(68, 63, 63); font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\">&nbsp;</span></li></ul><p></p>\r\n<p align=\"justify\" style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\"><span style=\"display: inline-block; border: none; padding: 0in\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">As\r\nTTC followers know, roasters like&nbsp;</font></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><u><a href=\"http://www.transparenttradecoffee.org/#!Bird-Rock-Roasters-More-Transparency-Data/cvxy/552207740cf21933cd3bf7b3\">Bird\r\nRock Coffee Roasters</a></u></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;and&nbsp;</font></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><u><a href=\"http://www.transparenttradecoffee.org/#!Counter-Culture-Two-Years-of-Transparency-Reports/cvxy/554a8f670cf248741715cd5b\">Counter\r\nCulture</a></u></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;take\r\nthe commitment to pricing transparency to the next level by\r\npublishing regular transparency reports. We aim to support these\r\ncommitments to transparency, and to help the sector make good on the\r\npromise and passion that are housed in the following statements:</font></font></font></span></p>\r\n<font face=\"Helvetica, serif\" style=\"font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\"><ul><li><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\" style=\"font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><font color=\"#443f3f\">Going\r\n	forward, we are also moving towards an even greater level\r\n	of&nbsp;transparency.” (</font></i></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><u><a href=\"http://birdrockcoffee.com/direct-trade-video/price-transparency/\">Bird\r\n	Rock Coffee Roasters</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\" style=\"font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><font color=\"#443f3f\">)</font></i></font></font><br></li><li><font color=\"#443f3f\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\">“<font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i>Sustainability\r\n	and&nbsp;transparency&nbsp;are core values for us, and these\r\n	concepts guide every decision me make.” (</i></font></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><u><a href=\"https://counterculturecoffee.com/contact/about-us\">Counter\r\n	Culture</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\" style=\"font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><font color=\"#443f3f\">)</font></i></font></font><br></li><li><font color=\"#443f3f\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\">“<font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i>Due\r\n	to the delicate balance of specifics, we must be vigilant – we\r\n	must seek out direct andtransparent&nbsp;relationships with coffee\r\n	growing professionals throughout the world. Directness\r\n	and&nbsp;transparency&nbsp;are important to us.” (</i></font></font></font><font color=\"#0000ff\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\"><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><u><a href=\"http://cqcoffeeroasters.com/pages/our-storied-coffees\">CQ\r\n	Coffee Roasters</a></u></i></font></font></font><font face=\"Helvetica, serif\" style=\"font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\"><font style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><i><font color=\"#443f3f\">)</font></i></font></font><br></li></ul></font>\r\n<p align=\"justify\" style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 0.25in\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">&nbsp;</font></p>\r\n<i style=\"font-family: Helvetica, serif; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\"><ol><li><i style=\"font-size: 1rem; line-height: 0.25in;\"><font color=\"#443f3f\">This\r\n	was done using a Google search option that supports searches within\r\n	specific websites. For example, ‘transparent site:\r\n	counterculturecoffee.com’ or ‘transparency site:\r\n	birdrockcoffeeroasters.com.’</font></i><br></li></ol></i>\r\n<p align=\"justify\" style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%\"><br>\r\n\r\n</p>\r\n<p align=\"justify\" style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%\"><br>\r\n\r\n</p>','462072294TT_TalkingT26.png','2015-06-17 15:25:13',9),(19,'Specialty Coffee Retail Price Index – 2015, Q2','specialty-coffee-retail-price-index-2015-q2','<font size=\"3\"><span style=\"color: rgb(20, 24, 35); font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; line-height: 19.3199996948242px;\">Specialty Coffee Retail Price Index (SCRPI)&nbsp;</span><font color=\"#141823\" face=\"helvetica, arial, sans-serif\"><span style=\"line-height: 19.3199996948242px;\">2015 Q2 released. Up 1.5%. Overall, the average price charged for roasted coffee at the end of June, 2015 was $21.94 per pound. &nbsp;The TT Coffee Team also explores SCRPI numbers to&nbsp;analyze how the&nbsp;</span></font><span style=\"color: rgb(20, 24, 35); font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; line-height: 19.3199996948242px;\">practice of naming coffee growers drives value.</span></font><span style=\"line-height:1.5em;\"><span style=\"font-family:helvetica-w01-light,helvetica-w02-light,sans-serif;\"><br><br></span></span><div align=\"center\"><span style=\"line-height:1.5em;\"><span style=\"font-family:helvetica-w01-light,helvetica-w02-light,sans-serif;\"><img src=\"http://transparenttradecoffee.com/app/uploads/blog/5931885788FHyQZM.jpg\" width=\"791\"></span></span><br><span style=\"line-height:1.5em;\"><span style=\"font-family:helvetica-w01-light,helvetica-w02-light,sans-serif;\"></span></span></div>','<span style=\"line-height:1.5em;\"><span style=\"font-family:helvetica-w01-light,helvetica-w02-light,sans-serif;\">In the second quarter of 2015, the&nbsp;<span style=\"text-decoration:underline;\"><a href=\"http://www.transparenttradecoffee.org/#%21scrpi2/c1fos\" target=\"_self\">Specialty Coffee Retail Price Index (SCRPI)</a></span>&nbsp;rose\r\n by 1.5%.[1] The average price for roasted specialty coffee at the end \r\nof June, 2015 was $21.94 per pound. This breaks down into an average of \r\n$16.15 per pound for the lowest-priced coffees (-0.1%), and $27.73 for \r\nthe highest-priced coffees (+2.5%) sold on the websites of the SCRPI \r\nroasters.<br><br><div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"http://i.imgur.com/KVu6P9c.jpg\" width=\"791\" style=\"line-height: 1.5em; font-size: 1rem;\"></div></span></span><br><p style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\" class=\"font_8\"><span style=\"line-height:1.5em;\"><span style=\"font-family:helvetica-w01-light,helvetica-w02-light,sans-serif;\">The\r\n year-over-year increase in specialty coffee prices – from the second \r\nquarter of 2014 to the second quarter of 2015 – was 12.5%. This broke \r\ndown into a 1.1% increase for the lowest-priced coffees, and a 20.9% \r\nincrease for the highest-priced coffees.</span></span></p><p style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\" class=\"font_8\"><span style=\"line-height:1.5em;\"><span style=\"font-family:helvetica-w01-light,helvetica-w02-light,sans-serif;\">Note that the corresponding&nbsp;<span style=\"text-decoration:underline;\"><a href=\"http://www.ico.org/prices/p2.htm\" target=\"_blank\">ICO Composite Price</a></span>&nbsp;for\r\n green coffee fell to $1.25 per pound in June, 2015. Thus, while retail \r\nprices for specialty coffees continued to rise, commodity prices fell \r\nanother 1.7% during the second quarter. Year-over-year, average retail \r\nprices for specialty coffees increased by 12.7%, while the ICO Composite\r\n Price fell by 17.8%</span></span></p><p class=\"font_8\"><b><span style=\"font-family:helvetica-w01-bold,helvetica-w02-bold,helvetica-lt-w10-bold,sans-serif;\">Supplementary Analysis – Naming Coffee Growers</span></b></p><span style=\"line-height:1.5em;\"><span style=\"font-family:helvetica-w01-light,helvetica-w02-light,sans-serif;\">While\r\n collecting 2015, Q2 SCRPI price data, we documented whether the name of\r\n the producing farm, farmer or cooperative was specifically mentioned on\r\n the web page that marketed each coffee. For example, when Blue Bottle \r\nCoffee sold its <span style=\"text-decoration:underline;\"><a href=\"https://bluebottlecoffee.com/store/brazil-faf-santa-clara-red-catuai-natural\" target=\"_blank\">Brazil FAF Santa Clara Red Catuai Natural</a></span> coffee, customers were told that “in the highlands of Divinolandia, Brazil, <span style=\"text-decoration:underline;\">Milton Nogueira, the esteemed producer of Santa Clara estate</span>, cares for his red Catuai coffee variety trees with a lot of pride.”<br><br></span></span><p style=\"line-height: 1.5em; text-align: justify;\" class=\"font_8\"><span style=\"line-height:1.5em;\"><span style=\"font-family:helvetica-w01-light,helvetica-w02-light,sans-serif;\">How\r\n prevalent is this practice of naming coffee growers? More than 60% (36 \r\nout of 58) of the highest-priced coffee listings in the 2015, Q2 SCRPI \r\nmentioned coffee growers by name. This percentage was just 12% (7 out of\r\n 58) for the lowest-priced coffee listings. The difference is explained \r\nin part by the fact that 44 out of the 58 lowest-priced coffees are \r\nblends and espressos, compared to only nine of the 58 highest-priced \r\ncoffees.</span></span></p><p style=\"line-height: 1.5em; text-align: justify;\" class=\"font_8\"><span style=\"line-height:1.5em;\"><span style=\"font-family:helvetica-w01-light,helvetica-w02-light,sans-serif;\">This\r\n suggests that a non-trivial number of coffee growers are being \r\nrecognized for the work that they do, and that this practice is more \r\ncommon among the more highly-valued coffees.</span></span></p><p style=\"line-height: 1.5em; text-align: justify;\" class=\"font_8\"><span style=\"line-height:1.5em;\"><span style=\"font-family:helvetica-w01-light,helvetica-w02-light,sans-serif;\">Does\r\n the specialty coffee market value knowing the identity of the coffee \r\ngrower? The following chart suggest that it does, but only at the high \r\nend of the market. Among the lowest-priced coffees in the 2015, Q2 \r\nSCRPI, the seven that made specific reference to the grower sold for an \r\naverage of $16.25 per pound, a $0.11 (0.7%) premium over the other \r\nlowest-priced coffees. Among the highest-priced coffees, the 36 that \r\nspecifically named the grower sold for an average of $29.99 per pound; \r\n$5.98 (24.9%) more than the average charged for the other highest-priced\r\n coffees.</span></span></p><div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"http://i.imgur.com/JV7U1nH.jpg\" width=\"688\" style=\"font-family: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 1.6;\"></div><br><span style=\"line-height:1.5em;\"><span style=\"font-family:helvetica-w01-light,helvetica-w02-light,sans-serif;\">These\r\n observations confirm that there is a tangible interest within the \r\nspecialty coffee market in knowing where coffees are coming from and who\r\n is growing the beans. Moreover, this willingness to name and charge \r\npremiums for specific coffee growers intensifies as we move from the \r\nlower to the higher end of the specialty coffee market.</span></span><br>','5931885788FHyQZM.jpg','2015-07-15 08:31:51',8),(20,' A Collective Look at the First Wave of Registered TT Coffees','a-collective-look-at-the-first-wave-of-registered-tt-coffees','<p style=\"margin-bottom: 6px; color: rgb(20, 24, 35); font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 19.3199996948242px;\">30 registered direct trade coffees from 8 different roasters have joined TT Coffee listings page in Q2 of 2015. How has the first wave of registered TT Coffees stacked up?&nbsp;<span style=\"line-height: 19.3199996948242px;\">The TT Coffee&nbsp;</span><span style=\"line-height: 19.3199996948242px;\">Team explores the list.</span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 6px; color: rgb(20, 24, 35); font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 19.3199996948242px;\"><span style=\"line-height: 19.3199996948242px;\"><br></span></p><p style=\"text-align: center; margin-bottom: 6px; color: rgb(20, 24, 35); font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 19.3199996948242px;\"><img src=\"http://static.wixstatic.com/media/054a02_f74184e82ca84949aff23f4244f15d00.png_srb_p_876_601_75_22_0.50_1.20_0.00_png_srb\"><span style=\"line-height: 19.3199996948242px;\"><br></span></p>','<p class=\"font_9\" style=\"margin-bottom: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; font-stretch: normal; line-height: 1.5em; font-family: helvetica-w01-roman, helvetica-w02-roman, helvetica-lt-w10-roman, sans-serif; color: rgb(68, 63, 63); text-align: justify; background: transparent;\"><span style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; border-image-source: initial; border-image-slice: initial; border-image-width: initial; border-image-outset: initial